She was involved in making [[:en:garments|garments]] for the [[kami]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jordan|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aqDC5bwx4_wC&dq=Wakahiru-me&pg=PA368|title=Dictionary of Gods and Goddesses|date=2014-05-14|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-0985-5|pages=346|language=en}}</ref> In some versions Wakahirume was killed when [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]] threw a flayed pony at her while she was in Amaterasu's weaving hall as written in the [[Nihon Shoki|Nihongi]].<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Coulter|first1=Charles Russell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sEIngqiKOugC&dq=Wakahirume&pg=PA503|title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Deities|last2=Turner|first2=Patricia|date=2013-07-04|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-96390-3|pages=503|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=169 |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto - Home : Kami in Classic Texts : Wakahirume |publisher=Eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp |date= |accessdate=2021-03-07}}</ref> The goddess also appears in the [[Jindaiki]] where the [[:en:Boat|Boat]] returning from [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]]'s sankan-gaisei (campaign for the three Korean kingdoms) tried to head to Nanba and could not go straight, they returned to Muko no minato Port ([[Kobe Port]]) to do some [[:en:Fortune-telling|Fortune-telling]]. Wakahirume no mikoto appeared and there was a [[:en:divine|divine]] [[message]], 'I would like to stay in Ikuta Nagao no kuni'. Thus, Unagami no Isachi was ordered to enshrine her. This is today's [[Ikuta Shrine]].
== References == <references /> ‎]]
]] {{Japan-myth-stub}}
